description: Field Notes - Lots of beautiful native orchids to be found in Langwarrin Flora and Fauna reserve. These purple donkey orchids were stunning!
Field Notes - Lots of beautiful native orchids to be found in Langwarrin Flora and Fauna reserve.
Found alongside walking track.

Field Notes - This beautiful flower is very small and dainty. It would be lovely to see this plant as an Australian gardens . Its leaves are only about 1-1.5cm wide usually folded in half making them seem smaller. The plant is sparse with only a few leaves. The leaves are bright green in colour. The 4th picture is an attempt to show the whole plant.  The flowers are on a long thin stem with multiple flowers on one stem in various stages of development. The flowers are approx. 15mm long and 15mm at its widest point.  They are bright sunshine yellow and can be seen a long way away. They have brown markings and are a "typical" orchid/dragon shape. The plant was found in a relatively undisturbed area. The  soil in fairly rocky, sandy and "poor" with a lot of other native plants nearby. The plant seems to have a "bulb" or something but we have not pulled on up to confirm this. As it seems to dies back and grow again each year. This plant was seen after the beautiful rain that we have had in this area recently.

description:
Yellow orchid with spreading rounded lateral petals, a hooded dorsal sepal, two rolled lateral sepals and a pointed yellow labellum had brownish-maroon markings and a central ridge. At the base of the labellum there were two hand-like extensions.  Several flowers sat at the top of the narrow stem. 
The narrow leaves formed a small clump at the base of the stem. 
The colony extended to both sides of the road and covered an area about 70m x 50m. The numerous plants flowered for about 3 weeks.

description:
Lemon yellow flower with pointed lateral petals and a pointed yellow labellum with a central ridge. The dorsal sepal curled slightly up at the tip while the striped greenish lateral sepals were rolled. 
The plant was part of a multispecies colony of orchids extending about 250m along the roadside, and varied in width from about 30m at its widest to about 1m along the fence at its narrowest.

description: This plant belongs to the family Orchidaceae. The flower matches the description within the Robinson which includes a zygomorphic flower organisation that is very specific to the family. This structure includes two lateral petals, 2 lower sepals, a dorsal sepal and a labellum. It is in the genus Diuris due to its distinct claws and overall structure that is described by PlantNet. For example, there are many free structures including the dorsal sepal, the lateral sepals and the lateral petals. The size and shape of the dorsal sepal and labellum are continuous with the PlantNet descriptions. This plant seems to be of the species Diuris aurea due to its yellow flowers with slight brown markings. It can be differentiated from Diuris sulphurea, a similar species, by the slight difference in colour and labellum ridges. The Diuris aurea is more golden and has two ridges within the callus of the labellum while the other species only has one ridge. Therefore, this species is Diuris aurea.
